\title{Counter Surveillance}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{Assess and harden operational security (OPSEC) posture for applications, communications, and infrastructure. Identifies surveillance exposure, metadata leakage, and tracking vectors. Use when auditing privacy-sensitive applications, reviewing OPSEC for threat models involving state-level adversaries, or hardening communications infrastructure.}

\subtree{
\title{Counter-Surveillance Security Skill}
\p{Trail of Bits-style defensive security assessment focused on surveillance resistance, metadata minimization, and operational security hardening.}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use}
\ul{
\li{Auditing privacy-sensitive applications}
\li{Reviewing journalist/activist threat models}
\li{Hardening communications platforms}
\li{Assessing metadata leakage in protocols and applications}
\li{Evaluating anonymous communication systems}
\li{Reviewing data retention and logging policies}
\li{Assessing exposure to lawful intercept and legal compulsion}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Threat Model Tiers}
\p{Structure analysis by adversary capability. Each tier subsumes the capabilities of all lower tiers.}

\pre{\startverb
| Tier | Adversary | Capabilities |
|------|-----------|-------------|
| **1** | Passive network observer | ISP, coffee shop WiFi, upstream AS. Sees DNS, IP flows, unencrypted traffic. |
| **2** | Active network attacker | MITM, DNS manipulation, BGP hijack, certificate compromise via rogue CA. |
| **3** | Platform-level adversary | Cloud provider, app store, OS vendor. Access to plaintext data at rest, push notification content, software update channel. |
| **4** | State-level | Lawful intercept (CALEA), FISA orders, national security letters with gag orders, IMSI catchers (Stingray), device exploit vendors (NSO Group). |
| **5** | Global passive adversary | Traffic analysis across jurisdictions, correlation attacks on anonymity networks, upstream cable taps (UPSTREAM/PRISM-class). |
\stopverb}

\p{Always define the threat tier before beginning an audit. Controls adequate for Tier 1 are meaningless against Tier 4.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Surveillance Surface Taxonomy}
\subtree{
\title{Network Metadata}
\ul{
\li{DNS queries (reveal browsing intent even with HTTPS)}
\li{TLS SNI field (reveals destination hostname in plaintext pre-ECH)}
\li{Connection timing and duration patterns}
\li{Packet sizes and inter-arrival times (traffic fingerprinting)}
\li{IP address correlation across sessions}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Application Metadata}
\ul{
\li{Push notification payloads (visible to Apple/Google)}
\li{App store analytics and telemetry}
\li{Crash reports containing device state}
\li{Update check frequency and timing}
\li{OAuth token exchanges revealing service usage}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Device Fingerprinting}
\ul{
\li{Browser fingerprint (canvas, WebGL, fonts, screen resolution)}
\li{Hardware identifiers (IMEI, MAC address, serial numbers)}
\li{Sensor data (accelerometer, gyroscope uniqueness)}
\li{Installed font and plugin enumeration}
\li{TLS client fingerprint (JA3/JA4)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Location Tracking}
\ul{
\li{GPS and GNSS precise positioning}
\li{Cell tower triangulation (passive, no user consent needed)}
\li{WiFi positioning (BSSID databases)}
\li{Bluetooth beacons and BLE scanning}
\li{IP geolocation databases}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Communications Metadata}
\ul{
\li{Who-talks-to-whom social graph (contact chaining)}
\li{Timing and frequency of communication}
\li{Message size and duration patterns}
\li{Group membership inference}
\li{Presence and online status indicators}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Financial Tracking}
\ul{
\li{Payment processor transaction logs}
\li{Blockchain analysis and address clustering}
\li{Loyalty program purchase correlation}
\li{ATM and POS location tracking}
\li{Subscription service usage patterns}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Audit Methodology}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Map data flows} — Diagram all metadata emission points from client to server to third party. Include DNS resolvers, CDNs, analytics, crash reporting, and push notification services.}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Assess encryption coverage} — Evaluate protection for data in transit (TLS 1.3, certificate pinning), at rest (full-disk encryption, per-record encryption), and in use (enclaves, MPC, FHE where applicable).}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Evaluate authentication without identification} — Can users authenticate to the service without revealing real-world identity? Review account creation flow, recovery mechanisms, and payment requirements.}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Review logging and data retention} — What identifiers are logged server-side? For how long? Under what legal jurisdiction? Can logs be compelled via subpoena, NSL, or FISA order?}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Test traffic analysis resistance} — Are encrypted messages padded to uniform size? Is timing randomized? Is cover traffic generated? Can an observer distinguish message types by size or pattern?}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Assess supply chain integrity} — Are builds reproducible? Are dependencies pinned and audited? Is the signing key air-gapped? Can users verify binary-to-source correspondence?}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Review jurisdiction and legal compulsion exposure} — Map server locations, corporate domicile, and applicable legal frameworks. Identify single points of legal compulsion (one subpoena reveals all user data).}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Code Review Patterns}
\p{Look for these anti-patterns in privacy-sensitive codebases:}

\pre{\startverb
# FINDING: Unnecessary logging of user identifiers
logger.info(f"Request from user {user_id} at {ip_address}")
# FIX: Log only what is operationally necessary; use rotating pseudonyms

# FINDING: Unpadded encrypted messages reveal content type
encrypted = encrypt(message)
# FIX: Pad all messages to fixed size buckets before encryption
encrypted = encrypt(pad_to_bucket(message))

# FINDING: Timestamps with unnecessary precision
created_at = datetime.utcnow()  # microsecond precision
# FIX: Round to reduce temporal fingerprinting
created_at = datetime.utcnow().replace(minute=0, second=0, microsecond=0)

# FINDING: Device identifiers transmitted to server
analytics.send(device_id=get_hardware_id())
# FIX: Use unlinkable session tokens; never transmit hardware IDs

# FINDING: DNS queries leaking browsing intent
requests.get("https://sensitive-site.org/resource")
# FIX: Enforce DNS-over-HTTPS/TLS; consider Tor for DNS resolution

# FINDING: Push notification content visible to platform provider
send_push(user, title="New message from Alice")
# FIX: Send empty/tombstone push; fetch content via E2E encrypted channel

# FINDING: Certificate pinning absent or bypassable
session = requests.Session()  # no pin validation
# FIX: Pin leaf or intermediate cert; detect and alert on pin failure
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Hardening Checklist}
\ul{
\li{[ ] \strong{Network anonymity} — Tor/onion routing for metadata-resistant connectivity}
\li{[ ] \strong{E2E encrypted messaging} — Signal protocol or equivalent with forward secrecy}
\li{[ ] \strong{Metadata-resistant protocols} — Sealed Sender, Private Information Retrieval, oblivious HTTP}
\li{[ ] \strong{Encrypted DNS} — DNS-over-HTTPS or DNS-over-TLS with trusted resolver; ECH for SNI}
\li{[ ] \strong{Reproducible builds} — Deterministic compilation; users can verify binary matches source}
\li{[ ] \strong{Air-gapped signing} — Software release signing keys on offline hardware}
\li{[ ] \strong{Memory-safe crypto} — Rust, Go, or formally verified C for cryptographic implementations}
\li{[ ] \strong{Minimal logging} — Log only what is operationally essential; auto-expire within days}
\li{[ ] \strong{Jurisdiction diversity} — Distribute infrastructure across non-cooperating legal jurisdictions}
\li{[ ] \strong{Warrant canary} — Publish regular signed statements of non-compromise; absence signals compulsion}
\li{[ ] \strong{Anonymous account creation} — No phone number, no email, no payment required}
\li{[ ] \strong{Forward secrecy} — Compromise of long-term keys does not reveal past communications}
}
}

